✅ Question:
If an image is added in the application after deployment, how do you handle it in Development and Production?

✅ High‑Level Client‑Ready Answer
	If an image is added after deployment, I do not hardcode it directly into the build.
	Instead, I manage it through environment‑specific asset management, such as static asset folders, cloud storage (S3 / CDN), or configuration‑based paths, ensuring no redeployment is required unless necessary.

✅ Standard Enterprise Approach
1️⃣ Development Environment
	• Image is added in: 
		○ public/assets folder OR
		○ Local storage bucket / mock CDN
	• Path is referenced using environment variables
	• Developers test the image locally without impacting prod
✅ Fast validation
✅ No production impact

2️⃣ Production Environment
Images are never manually dropped into the deployed build.
Instead, one of these approaches is used:
✅ Option 1: CDN / Cloud Storage (Preferred)
	• Upload image to: 
		○ AWS S3
		○ Azure Blob
		○ GCP Bucket
	• Served through CDN
	• Application references it via URL
✅ No redeployment
✅ Better performance
✅ Cache‑friendly

✅ Option 2: Static Asset via Pipeline
Used only if image is part of UI layout
Steps:
	1. Add image to repository
	2. Commit the change
	3. CI/CD pipeline runs
	4. Application redeployed
✅ Controlled
❌ Requires redeploy

✅ Option 3: CMS / Backend‑Driven
For dynamic content:
	• Backend or CMS stores image URL
	• Frontend reads image from API response
✅ No UI redeploy
✅ Business‑controlled updates

✅ Environment Handling (Important Interview Point)
I use environment‑based configuration:

DEV → dev-cdn-url/images
UAT → uat-cdn-url/images
PROD → prod-cdn-url/images
This ensures:
	• Same code works everywhere
	• Images differ per environment
	• No hardcoding

✅ Caching & Versioning
To avoid cache issues:
	• Use versioned image names or query params
	• CDN cache invalidation if required
Example:
logo_v2.png

✅ Security & Access
	• Production buckets are read‑only for UI
	• Upload permissions restricted
	• Sensitive images are access‑controlled

✅ One‑Line Power Answer (Very Useful in Interview)
	For post‑deployment image changes, I prefer hosting them on a CDN or cloud storage and configure environment‑specific URLs, so images can be updated independently without redeploying the application.

✅ If Interviewer Asks Follow‑Up: “Will you redeploy for image change?”
Answer:
	• ❌ Not for content images
	• ✅ Only for UI/layout‑dependent assets
	• ✅ CDN/CMS preferred for flexibility

✅ Domain‑Specific Examples
🛒 eCommerce
	• Product banners → CDN
	• Promo images → CMS driven
🏦 Insurance
	• Policy graphics → backend controlled
	• Regulatory banners → no UI redeploy

